paragraphs.title: Zeppelin Demo Notebook 4
paragraphs.text:
%md
Demonstrate loading, querying, visualizing, and saving the GroupLens MovieLens Latest Datasets from an [Amazon RDS PostgreSQL](https://aws.amazon.com/rds/postgresql/) database.

paragraphs.title: Set all Variable Values
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark
# change me
ZEPPELIN_DEMO_BUCKET="gstafford-emr-demo-us-east1"
RDS_URL="zeppelin-demo.c6louiq8ibk3.us-east-1.rds.amazonaws.com"
RDS_USER="masteruser"
RDS_PASSWORD="5up3r53cr3tPa55w0rd"

# don't change me
RDS_DRIVER="org.postgresql.Driver"
RDS_PORT="5432"
RDS_DATABASE="ratings"

RDS_JDBC="jdbc:postgresql://" + RDS_URL + ":" + RDS_PORT + "/" + RDS_DATABASE
print("RDS_JDBC:", RDS_JDBC)
RDS_CONN_STR = "host=" + RDS_URL + " port=" + RDS_PORT + " dbname=" + RDS_DATABASE + " user=" + RDS_USER + " password=" + RDS_PASSWORD
print("RDS_CONN_STR:", RDS_CONN_STR)

paragraphs.title: Load MovieLens Data from GroupLens
paragraphs.text:
%sh
#change me - choices: or ml-latest-small (100k) or ml-latest (27MM)
DIR="ml-latest-small"

if [ -d $DIR ]; then
    echo "$DIR exist"
else 
    wget -nv http://files.grouplens.org/datasets/movielens/$DIR.zip -O $DIR.zip && unzip $DIR.zip
fi

# copy from local file system (/var/lib/zeppelin) to the destination file system (/user/zeppelin)
hadoop fs -put -f  $DIR/movies.csv $DIR/ratings.csv .
hadoop fs -ls -h .

paragraphs.title: Create Spark Session
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark
from pyspark import SparkFiles
from pyspark.sql import SparkSession
from pyspark.sql.types import StructType, StructField, StringType, IntegerType, DateType

spark = SparkSession \
    .builder \
    .appName("pyspark_demo_app") \
    .getOrCreate()

paragraphs.title: Download DDL from S3 and Execute Against RDS
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark
import boto3
import psycopg2
import csv

s3 = boto3.client('s3')
s3.download_file(ZEPPELIN_DEMO_BUCKET, "bootstrap/ratings.sql", "ratings.sql")

conn = psycopg2.connect(RDS_CONN_STR)
conn.autocommit = True
cursor = conn.cursor()

sql_file = open("ratings.sql", "r")
sqlFile = sql_file.read()
sql_file.close()
sqlCommands = sqlFile.split(";")
for command in sqlCommands:
    print(command)
    if command.strip() != "":
        cursor.execute(command)

paragraphs.title: Import Movies from CSV File to RDS
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark
# source: https://www.dataquest.io/blog/loading-data-into-postgres/
# the slow way since the titles contain commas
with open("ml-latest-small/movies.csv", "r") as f:
    reader = csv.reader(f)
    next(reader)  # Skip the header row.
    for row in reader:
        cursor.execute(
            "INSERT INTO movies (movieId, title, genres) VALUES (%s, %s, %s)",
            row
        )
        conn.commit()

paragraphs.title: Import Ratings from CSV File to RDS
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark
# the fast way...
with open("ml-latest-small/ratings.csv", "r") as f:
    # Notice that we don"t need the `csv` module.
    next(f) # Skip the header row.
    cursor.copy_from(f, "ratings", sep=",", columns=("userId", "movieId", "rating", "timestamp"))
    conn.commit()

paragraphs.title: Load Movies Data from RDS into DataFrame
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark
RDS_TABLE="movies"

moviesDF = spark.read \
    .format("jdbc") \
    .option("driver",RDS_DRIVER) \
    .option("url", RDS_JDBC) \
    .option("user",RDS_USER) \
    .option("password", RDS_PASSWORD) \
    .option("dbtable", RDS_TABLE) \
    .load()

print("DataFrame rows: %d" % moviesDF.count())
print("DataFrame schema: %s" % moviesDF)
moviesDF.show(10, False)

paragraphs.title: Load Ratings Data from RDS into DataFrame
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark
RDS_TABLE="ratings"

ratingsDF = spark.read \
    .format("jdbc") \
    .option("driver",RDS_DRIVER) \
    .option("url", RDS_JDBC) \
    .option("user",RDS_USER) \
    .option("password", RDS_PASSWORD) \
    .option("dbtable", RDS_TABLE) \
    .load()

print("DataFrame rows: %d" % ratingsDF.count())
print("DataFrame schema: %s" % ratingsDF)
ratingsDF.show(10, False)

paragraphs.title: Create Temporary View and Query Data using SQL
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark
ratingsDF.createOrReplaceTempView("ratings")
moviesDF.createOrReplaceTempView("movies")

topMoviesDF = spark.sql("SELECT m.title, CAST(AVG(r.rating) AS DECIMAL(3,2)) as avg_rating, COUNT(r.rating) as cnt_ratings " +
                        "FROM ratings r " +
                        "JOIN movies m ON (r.movieId = m.movieId) " +
                        "GROUP BY m.title " +
                        "ORDER BY avg_rating DESC, cnt_ratings DESC, m.title ASC")
                        
topMoviesDF = topMoviesDF.filter(topMoviesDF.cnt_ratings >= 25)

print("DataFrame rows: %d" % moviesDF.count())
print("Top 10 Movies")
topMoviesDF.show(10, False)

%postgre
SELECT table_schema, table_catalog, table_name
FROM information_schema.tables
WHERE table_schema='public'
ORDER BY table_schema, table_catalog, table_name;

paragraphs.title: Query RDS Database using Zeppelin JDBC PostgreSQL Interpreter
paragraphs.text:
%postgre
WITH tmp_table AS (
    SELECT m.title, AVG(r.rating) as avg_rating, COUNT(r.rating) as cnt_ratings
    FROM ratings r
    JOIN movies m ON (r.movieId = m.movieId)
    GROUP BY m.title)
    
SELECT title, CAST(avg_rating AS DECIMAL(3,2)), cnt_ratings
FROM tmp_table
WHERE avg_rating > ${avgRatingMin=4} AND cnt_ratings >= ${RatingsMin=100}
ORDER BY avg_rating ASC, cnt_ratings DESC, title ASC
LIMIT 25;
